{"title_page": "Sanders of the River", "text_new": "{{short description|1935 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sanders of the River<br>Alternate title: Bosambo\n| image          = Sanders_River_35.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Zolt\u00e1n Korda]]\n| producer       = [[Alexander Korda]]\n| writer         = [[Lajos B\u00edr\u00f3]]<br>[[Jeffrey Dell]]<br>[[Edgar Wallace]]<br>[[Arthur Wimperis]]\n| starring       = [[Leslie Banks]]<br>[[Paul Robeson]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Osmond Borradaile<br>[[Louis Page (cinematographer)|Louis Page]]<br>[[Georges P\u00e9rinal]]\n| editing        = [[Charles Crichton]]\n| studio         = [[London Films]]\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{film date|1935|4|8|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 98 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom \n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''Sanders of the River''''' is a 1935 British film directed by the Hungarian-British director, [[Zolt\u00e1n Korda]], based on the stories of [[Edgar Wallace]]. It is set in [[Colonial Nigeria|British Nigeria]]. The lead Nigerian characters were played by African-Americans [[Paul Robeson]] and [[Nina Mae McKinney]]. The film proved a significant commercial and critical success, giving Korda the first of his four nominations for Best Film at the Venice Film Festival.\n\n==Plot==\nSanders ([[Leslie Banks]]) is a British colonial [[District Commissioner (British Colonial)|District Commissioner]] in [[Colonial Nigeria]]. He tries to rule his province fairly, including the various tribes comprising the Peoples of the River. He is regarded with respect by some and with fear by others, among whom he is referred to as \"Sandi\" and \"Lord Sandi\". He has an ally in Bosambo, a literate and educated chief (played by the American actor, [[Paul Robeson]]).\n\nWhen Sanders goes on leave, another chief, King Mofolaba, spreads the rumour that \"Sandi is dead.\" Inter-tribal war seems inevitable, and the situation is made worse by gun-runners and slavers.\n\nHis relief, Ferguson (known to the natives as Lord Ferguson), is unequal to the task; he is captured and killed by King Mofolaba. Sanders returns to restore peace. When Bosambo's wife Lilongo ([[Nina Mae McKinney]]) is kidnapped, the chief tracks down her kidnappers. Captured by them, he is saved by a relief force commanded by Sanders. Bosambo kills King Mofolaba and is subsequently named by Sanders as the King of the Peoples of the River.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Leslie Banks]] as Commissioner R.G. Sanders\n* [[Paul Robeson]] as Bosambo\n* [[Orlando Martins]] as K'Lova\n* [[Nina Mae McKinney]] as Lilongo\n* [[Martin Walker (actor)|Martin Walker]] as J. Ferguson\n* Robert Cochran as Lieutenant Tibbets (as Robert Cochrane)\n* Richard Grey as Captain Hamilton\n* Toto Ware as King Mofolaba\n* Marqu\u00e9s De Portago as Farini\n* [[Eric Maturin]] as Smith\n* [[Allan Jeayes]] as Father O'Leary\n* [[Charles Carson (actor)|Charles Carson]] as Sir John\n* [[Jomo Kenyatta]] as Tribal Leader\n\nColonia administrator [[Bernard Henry Bourdillon|Sir B. Bourdillon]] is credited as an adviser.\n\n==Paul Robeson disowns the film==\n[[File:Paul Robeson and \u00c1gay Ir\u00e9n - London, 1934.tif|thumb|upright|Actor [[Paul Robeson]] and actress [[Ir\u00e9n \u00c1gay]] on the set of ''Sanders of the River'', London, 1934]]\nThe [[African-American]] singer and actor [[Paul Robeson]], a civil rights activist, accepted the role of Bosambo while living in London. At the time, he was studying the roots of pan-African culture through studies of language and music. He felt that if he could portray the Nigerian leader, Bosambo, with cultural accuracy and dignity, he could help audiences\u2014especially Black audiences\u2014to understand and respect the roots of Black culture. He took the role on the condition that the film would portray Africans positively.<ref name=\"bfiscron\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/438878/index.html|title=Sanders of the River (1935)|last=Duguid|first=Mark|work=BFI Screenonline|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=9 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe filmmakers took an unusual step towards authenticity by sending a film crew on a four-month voyage into remote areas of Africa. They recorded traditional African dances and ceremonies, with the intention of using this footage integrated with scenes shot in the studio that included the future President and Prime Minister of Kenya [[Jomo Kenyatta]] as one of the [[film extra|extras]].<ref>pp. 199-200 Neame, Ronald with Cooper, Barbara Roisman ''Straight from the Horse's Mouth: Ronald Neame, an Autobiography'' Scarecrow Press, 27 September 2003</ref>\n\nAfter the filming, Robeson was asked back to the studio for retakes of some scenes. He discovered that the film\u2019s message had been changed during editing; it seemed to justify imperialism and upholding the \"[[White Man's Burden]].\" The finished film was dedicated to \"the handful of white men whose everyday work is an unsung saga of courage and efficiency\".<ref>[http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/445836/index.html \"Korda and Empire\"], BFI screenonline page</ref>\n\nBosambo was changed from a Nigerian leader to a servile lackey of British colonial rule. Robeson was furious and complained:\n<blockquote>The imperialist plot had been placed in the plot during the last days five days of shooting...I was roped into the picture because I wanted to portray the culture of the African people and I committed a ''faux pas'' which convinced me that I had failed to weigh the problems of 150,000,000 native Africans...I hate the picture.<ref>Duberman, Martin, ''Paul Robeson: The Discovery of Africa,'' 1989, p. 182.</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 1938, Robeson added disparagingly: \"It is the only film of mine that can be shown in Italy or Germany, for it shows the negro as Fascist states desire him - savage and childish.\"<ref>Duberman (1989),  ''Paul Robeson'', p. 180.</ref>\n\nRobeson was so disillusioned by the picture that he attempted, but failed, to buy back all the prints to prevent it from being shown.<ref>Robeson, Susan, ''A Pictorial Biography of Paul Robeson: The Whole World in His Hands'', 1981, p. 73.</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIt was the 11th most popular film at the British box office in 1935-36.<ref>\"The Film Business in the United States and Britain during the 1930s\" by John Sedgwick and Michael Pokorny, ''The Economic History Review''New Series, Vol. 58, No. 1 (Feb. 2005), pp.79-112</ref>\n\n==Other versions==\nThe film was parodied in [[Will Hay]]'s 1938 film ''[[Old Bones of the River]]''. This comedy featured characters named Commissioner Sanders, Captain Hamilton and Bosambo.<ref name=\"bfiscronob\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/447266/index.html|title=Old Bones of the River (1938)|last=Collinson|first=Gavin|work=BFI Screenonline|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=9 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1963 producer [[Harry Alan Towers]] made a German/British [[international co-production]] small scale version of the film, ''[[Death Drums Along the River]]'' set in the modern day only using some of the names of the characters. It spawned a sequel, ''[[Coast of Skeletons]]'' (1965).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0026966|title=Sanders of the River}}\n* {{Amg movie|42805|Sanders of the River}} (Alternate title: Bosambo)\n\n{{Zoltan Korda}}\n{{Alexander Korda}}\n{{Edgar Wallace}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sanders Of The River}}\n[[Category:1935 films]]\n[[Category:1930s adventure drama films]]\n[[Category:British black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about race and ethnicity]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Zolt\u00e1n Korda]]\n[[Category:Films set in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Films set in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Edgar Wallace]]\n[[Category:Paul Robeson]]\n[[Category:British adventure drama films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Alexander Korda]]\n[[Category:Works about colonialism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1935 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sanders of the River<br>Alternate title: Bosambo\n| image          = Sanders_River_35.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Zolt\u00e1n Korda]]\n| producer       = [[Alexander Korda]]\n| writer         = [[Lajos B\u00edr\u00f3]]<br>Jeffrey Dell<br>[[Edgar Wallace]]<br>Arthur Wimperis\n| starring       = [[Leslie Banks]]<br>[[Paul Robeson]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Osmond Borradaile<br>[[Louis Page (cinematographer)|Louis Page]]<br>[[Georges P\u00e9rinal]]\n| editing        = [[Charles Crichton]]\n| studio         = [[London Films]]\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{film date|1935|4|8|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 98 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom \n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''Sanders of the River''''' is a 1935 British film directed by the Hungarian-British director, [[Zolt\u00e1n Korda]], based on the stories of [[Edgar Wallace]]. It is set in [[Colonial Nigeria|British Nigeria]]. The lead Nigerian characters were played by African-Americans [[Paul Robeson]] and [[Nina Mae McKinney]]. The film proved a significant commercial and critical success, giving Korda the first of his four nominations for Best Film at the Venice Film Festival.\n\n==Plot==\nSanders ([[Leslie Banks]]) is a British colonial [[District Commissioner (British Colonial)|District Commissioner]] in [[Colonial Nigeria]]. He tries to rule his province fairly, including the various tribes comprising the Peoples of the River. He is regarded with respect by some and with fear by others, among whom he is referred to as \"Sandi\" and \"Lord Sandi\". He has an ally in Bosambo, a literate and educated chief (played by the American actor, [[Paul Robeson]]).\n\nWhen Sanders goes on leave, another chief, King Mofolaba, spreads the rumour that \"Sandi is dead.\" Inter-tribal war seems inevitable, and the situation is made worse by gun-runners and slavers.\n\nHis relief, Ferguson (known to the natives as Lord Ferguson), is unequal to the task; he is captured and killed by King Mofolaba. Sanders returns to restore peace. When Bosambo's wife Lilongo ([[Nina Mae McKinney]]) is kidnapped, the chief tracks down her kidnappers. Captured by them, he is saved by a relief force commanded by Sanders. Bosambo kills King Mofolaba and is subsequently named by Sanders as the King of the Peoples of the River.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Leslie Banks]] as Commissioner R.G. Sanders\n* [[Paul Robeson]] as Bosambo\n* [[Orlando Martins]] as K'Lova\n* [[Nina Mae McKinney]] as Lilongo\n* [[Martin Walker (actor)|Martin Walker]] as J. Ferguson\n* Robert Cochran as Lieutenant Tibbets (as Robert Cochrane)\n* Richard Grey as Captain Hamilton\n* Toto Ware as King Mofolaba\n* Marqu\u00e9s De Portago as Farini\n* [[Eric Maturin]] as Smith\n* [[Allan Jeayes]] as Father O'Leary\n* [[Charles Carson (actor)|Charles Carson]] as Sir John\n* [[Jomo Kenyatta]] as Tribal Leader\n\nColonia administrator [[Bernard Henry Bourdillon|Sir B. Bourdillon]] is credited as an adviser.\n\n==Paul Robeson disowns the film==\n[[File:Paul Robeson and \u00c1gay Ir\u00e9n - London, 1934.tif|thumb|upright|Actor [[Paul Robeson]] and actress [[Ir\u00e9n \u00c1gay]] on the set of ''Sanders of the River'', London, 1934]]\nThe [[African-American]] singer and actor [[Paul Robeson]], a civil rights activist, accepted the role of Bosambo while living in London. At the time, he was studying the roots of pan-African culture through studies of language and music. He felt that if he could portray the Nigerian leader, Bosambo, with cultural accuracy and dignity, he could help audiences\u2014especially Black audiences\u2014to understand and respect the roots of Black culture. He took the role on the condition that the film would portray Africans positively.<ref name=\"bfiscron\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/438878/index.html|title=Sanders of the River (1935)|last=Duguid|first=Mark|work=BFI Screenonline|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=9 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe filmmakers took an unusual step towards authenticity by sending a film crew on a four-month voyage into remote areas of Africa. They recorded traditional African dances and ceremonies, with the intention of using this footage integrated with scenes shot in the studio that included the future President and Prime Minister of Kenya [[Jomo Kenyatta]] as one of the [[film extra|extras]].<ref>pp. 199-200 Neame, Ronald with Cooper, Barbara Roisman ''Straight from the Horse's Mouth: Ronald Neame, an Autobiography'' Scarecrow Press, 27 September 2003</ref>\n\nAfter the filming, Robeson was asked back to the studio for retakes of some scenes. He discovered that the film\u2019s message had been changed during editing; it seemed to justify imperialism and upholding the \"[[White Man's Burden]].\" The finished film was dedicated to \"the handful of white men whose everyday work is an unsung saga of courage and efficiency\".<ref>[http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/445836/index.html \"Korda and Empire\"], BFI screenonline page</ref>\n\nBosambo was changed from a Nigerian leader to a servile lackey of British colonial rule. Robeson was furious and complained:\n<blockquote>The imperialist plot had been placed in the plot during the last days five days of shooting...I was roped into the picture because I wanted to portray the culture of the African people and I committed a ''faux pas'' which convinced me that I had failed to weigh the problems of 150,000,000 native Africans...I hate the picture.<ref>Duberman, Martin, ''Paul Robeson: The Discovery of Africa,'' 1989, p. 182.</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 1938, Robeson added disparagingly: \"It is the only film of mine that can be shown in Italy or Germany, for it shows the negro as Fascist states desire him - savage and childish.\"<ref>Duberman (1989),  ''Paul Robeson'', p. 180.</ref>\n\nRobeson was so disillusioned by the picture that he attempted, but failed, to buy back all the prints to prevent it from being shown.<ref>Robeson, Susan, ''A Pictorial Biography of Paul Robeson: The Whole World in His Hands'', 1981, p. 73.</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIt was the 11th most popular film at the British box office in 1935-36.<ref>\"The Film Business in the United States and Britain during the 1930s\" by John Sedgwick and Michael Pokorny, ''The Economic History Review''New Series, Vol. 58, No. 1 (Feb. 2005), pp.79-112</ref>\n\n==Other versions==\nThe film was parodied in [[Will Hay]]'s 1938 film ''[[Old Bones of the River]]''. This comedy featured characters named Commissioner Sanders, Captain Hamilton and Bosambo.<ref name=\"bfiscronob\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/447266/index.html|title=Old Bones of the River (1938)|last=Collinson|first=Gavin|work=BFI Screenonline|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=9 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1963 producer [[Harry Alan Towers]] made a German/British [[international co-production]] small scale version of the film, ''[[Death Drums Along the River]]'' set in the modern day only using some of the names of the characters. It spawned a sequel, ''[[Coast of Skeletons]]'' (1965).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0026966|title=Sanders of the River}}\n* {{Amg movie|42805|Sanders of the River}} (Alternate title: Bosambo)\n\n{{Zoltan Korda}}\n{{Alexander Korda}}\n{{Edgar Wallace}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sanders Of The River}}\n[[Category:1935 films]]\n[[Category:1930s adventure drama films]]\n[[Category:British black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about race and ethnicity]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Zolt\u00e1n Korda]]\n[[Category:Films set in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Films set in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Edgar Wallace]]\n[[Category:Paul Robeson]]\n[[Category:British adventure drama films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Alexander Korda]]\n[[Category:Works about colonialism]]\n", "name_user": "Beryl reid fan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding links.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanders_of_the_River"}
{"title_page": "Rifles for Watie", "text_new": "{{Infobox book  | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_bovels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name           = Rifles for Watie\n| title_orig     = \n| translator     = \n| image          = HaroldKeith RiflesForWatie.jpg\n|caption = Cover of the 1991 reissue hardback\n| author         = [[Harold Keith]]\n| cover_artist   =  \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| series         = \n| genre          = [[Historical novel|Historical]], [[War novel|War]]\n| publisher      = [[Thomas Y. Crowell]] \n| release_date   = 1957\n| media_type     = Print ([[Hardback]] & [[Paperback]])\n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n\n'''''Rifles for Watie''''' is a [[children's literature|children's novel]] by American writer [[Harold Keith]]. It was first published in [[1957 in literature|1957]], and received the [[Newbery Medal]] the following year.\n\nSet during the [[American Civil War]], the plot revolves around the fictional sixteen-year-old Jefferson Davis Bussey, who is caught up in the events of history. Actual historical personages (e.g. Generals [[Stand Watie]] and [[James G. Blunt]]) and battles (e.g. [[Battle of Wilson's Creek|Wilson's Creek]] and [[Battle of Prairie Grove|Prairie Grove]]) are seen from the viewpoint of an ordinary soldier, enabled by the choice of protagonist. Harold Keith spent many years interviewing Civil War veterans and visiting the sites depicted in the book, resulting in an authenticity that is rare for historical fiction that targets a young adult audience.\n\nThe setting, west of the Mississippi, is also not typical of Civil War novels, so the reader gets a perspective on the war not generally available in other books, let alone one found in children's books.\n\n==Plot summary==\nJefferson Davis Bussey marches off to [[Leavenworth, Kansas|Leavenworth]] from [[Linn County, Kansas]] in 1861, on his way to join the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] volunteers. He is off to fight for the North, his zeal having been fueled by reaction to the guerilla war of \"bushwhackers\" that was taking place in eastern Kansas. However, Stand Watie is on the side of the [[Confederate States of America|South]]. We meet many soldiers and civilians on both sides of the war, including Watie's raiding parties, itinerant printer Noah Babbitt and, in [[Tahlequah, Oklahoma|Tahlequah]], [[Indian Territory]] (now [[Oklahoma]]) the beautiful [[Cherokee]] girl, Lucy Washbourne. During an undercover mission, Jeff finds that Captain Asa Clardy of the Union Cavalry is smuggling new [[Spencer rifles]] to the Indian forces of [[Stand Watie]]. \n\nJeff winds up fighting for both the North and the South (while on a special undercover mission) during the conflict while making friends on each side. The book is also notable for the detailed depiction of contemporary Cherokee life in Indian Territory, including various tribal political factions. Keith portrays the difficulties Jeff Bussey faces in choosing one side or the other in the midst of huge conflicts.\n\nBELIVE IN GOD AND UR LIFE WILL CHANGE GIVE IT A CHANCE PLZ'''Bold text'''\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' said of the book: \"Stirring, original and always credible, this is distinctly superior.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/harold-keith-4/rifles-for-watie-2/ |journal=[[Kirkus Reviews]] |title=RIFLES FOR WATIE by Harold Keith |access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> In a retrospective essay about the Newbery Medal-winning books from 1956 to 1965, librarian Carolyn Horovitz wrote of ''Rifles for Watie'', ''[[Carry On, Mr. Bowditch]]'', ''[[The Witch of Blackbird Pond]]'' and ''[[The Bronze Bow]]'': \"All have value, all are told skilfully. If they lack the qualities of greatness, it is largely because their style has a commercial sameness.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Horovitz |first=Carolyn |chapter=Only the Best |page=[https://archive.org/details/newberycaldecott00king/page/160 160] |title=Newbery and Caldecott Medal Books: 1956-1965 |url=https://archive.org/details/newberycaldecott00king |url-access=registration |editor-last=Kingman |editor-first=Lee |publisher=[[The Horn Book Magazine|The Horn Book, Incorporated]] |location=[[Boston]] |year=1965 |lccn=65-26759}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* Winner, 1958 Newbery Medal\n* Notable Children's Books of 1957 (ALA)\n* 1964 James Carroll Shelf Award\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book | title=Rifles for Watide on Rifles for Watie | last= | first= | work=BookRags Study Guides | url=http://www.bookrags.com/studyguide-rifles-for-watie/ | date= | accessdate=2007-06-26 }}\n*{{cite book | title=Newbery and Caldecott Medal Books: 1956-1965 | url=https://archive.org/details/newberycaldecott00king | url-access=registration | last=Kingman | first=Lee (ed.) | publisher=Horn Book | location=Boston | year=1965 }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Newbery Medal|Newbery Medal recipient]]|before=''[[Miracles on Maple Hill]]''|after=''[[The Witch of Blackbird Pond]]''|years=[[1958 in literature|1958]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:1957 American novels]]\n[[Category:American Civil War novels]]\n[[Category:Children's historical novels]]\n[[Category:Newbery Medal-winning works]]\n[[Category:American children's novels]]\n[[Category:1957 children's books]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Kansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book  | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_bovels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name           = Rifles for Watie\n| title_orig     = \n| translator     = \n| image          = HaroldKeith RiflesForWatie.jpg\n|caption = Cover of the 1991 reissue hardback\n| author         = [[Harold Keith]]\n| cover_artist   =  \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| series         = \n| genre          = [[Historical novel|Historical]], [[War novel|War]]\n| publisher      = [[Thomas Y. Crowell]] \n| release_date   = 1957\n| media_type     = Print ([[Hardback]] & [[Paperback]])\n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n\n'''''Rifles for Watie''''' is a [[children's literature|children's novel]] by American writer [[Harold Keith]]. It was first published in [[1957 in literature|1957]], and received the [[Newbery Medal]] the following year.\n\nSet during the [[American Civil War]], the plot revolves around the fictional sixteen-year-old Jefferson Davis Bussey, who is caught up in the events of history. Actual historical personages (e.g. Generals [[Stand Watie]] and [[James G. Blunt]]) and battles (e.g. [[Battle of Wilson's Creek|Wilson's Creek]] and [[Battle of Prairie Grove|Prairie Grove]]) are seen from the viewpoint of an ordinary soldier, enabled by the choice of protagonist. Harold Keith spent many years interviewing Civil War veterans and visiting the sites depicted in the book, resulting in an authenticity that is rare for historical fiction that targets a young adult audience.\n\nThe setting, west of the Mississippi, is also not typical of Civil War novels, so the reader gets a perspective on the war not generally available in other books, let alone one found in children's books.\n\n==Plot summary==\nJefferson Davis Bussey marches off to [[Leavenworth, Kansas|Leavenworth]] from [[Linn County, Kansas]] in 1861, on his way to join the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] volunteers. He is off to fight for the North, his zeal having been fueled by reaction to the guerilla war of \"bushwhackers\" that was taking place in eastern Kansas. However, Stand Watie is on the side of the [[Confederate States of America|South]]. We meet many soldiers and civilians on both sides of the war, including Watie's raiding parties, itinerant printer Noah Babbitt and, in [[Tahlequah, Oklahoma|Tahlequah]], [[Indian Territory]] (now [[Oklahoma]]) the beautiful [[Cherokee]] girl, Lucy Washbourne. During an undercover mission, Jeff finds that Captain Asa Clardy of the Union Cavalry is smuggling new [[Spencer rifles]] to the Indian forces of [[Stand Watie]]. \n\nJeff winds up fighting for both the North and the South (while on a special undercover mission) during the conflict while making friends on each side. The book is also notable for the detailed depiction of contemporary Cherokee life in Indian Territory, including various tribal political factions. Keith portrays the difficulties Jeff Bussey faces in choosing one side or the other in the midst of huge conflicts.\n\n==Characters==\n*Jefferson (Jeff) Davis Bussey &ndash; the protagonist. Originally an infantry private but later his whole company is trained as cavalrymen. After a long secret mission and daring escape he is promoted to sergeant and sent home.\n*Lucy Washbourne &ndash; Jeff's love interest, a young woman living in [[Tahlequah, Oklahoma]] (then [[Indian Territory]])\n*Lee Washbourne &ndash; Lucy's brother, a Confederate soldier and scout. Killed by a firing squad in which Jeff unknowingly took a part. Jeff, however, did not shoot and did not realize that it was Lee, whom he had heard about from Lucy and Mrs. Washbourne, until he saw Lee's name engraved on his watch.\n*Noah Babbitt &ndash; an itinerant printer, older than Jeff, and a Union soldier and a lover of nature.\n*[[Stand Watie]] &ndash; historical character, the last Confederate general to surrender at the war's end. His forces are described as \"using old British one shot Enfield's and double barrel shotguns.\" The use of Spencer repeaters could mean a victory against Union soldiers.\n*[[James G. Blunt]] &ndash; historical character, Union general who battled to control [[Indian Territory]].\n*David Gardner &ndash; Jeff's hometown friend who joins the [[Union Army]] with him.\n*John Chadwick &ndash; Another of Jeff's hometown friends who joins the [[Union Army]] with him. \n*Captain Asa Clardy &ndash; Jeff's commanding officer in the [[Union Army]], and a major antagonist against Jeff. He is the one smuggling the Spencer Rifles to the Rebels. Eventually found killed and exposed postmortem as a traitor.\n*Heifer Hobbs &ndash; company cook and mentor for Jeff in the rebel army of Stand Watie.  He stands up for Jeff when Sergent Fields accuses Jeff of being a Union spy.\n*Bill Earle &ndash; A singer who served with Jeff made in the war, on the Union side\n*Stuart Mitchell - A Union P.O.W who was able to escape from Watie's men and enlist in Jeff's unit. \n*Pete Millholland &ndash; An older gentleman who is elected as Jeff's squad leader. He's killed by Rebels while cooking supper in Choctaw country\n*Jimmy - The 14-year-old drummer boy for the Union army. He is critically injured and later dies on [[Christmas Day]]\n*Edith Bussey - Jeff's Mom\n*Emory Bussey - Jeff's father\n*Ring - Jeff's dog in Kansas\n*Dixie - A dog owned by a rebel who is killed at the [[Battle of Wilson's Creek]]. Jeff befriends her and keeps her, later leaving her with Lucy Washbourne.\n*Keegan - A commander for the Confederates.\n*Lieutenant Orff -  Commander of the scout platoon that Jeff and Noah join after becoming cavalrymen. Carries a Spencer 7 shot rifle.\n* Sully - A \"bloodhound\" that is supposed to be hunting Jeff when he befriends him. Sully also looks very sad and ugly. \n*Sergeant Fields - [[Non-commissioned officer|NCO]] for the company of Confederate cavalry Jeff joins.\n*Jim Bostwick - a scout that Jeff works with. Killed in a battle while posing as a Confederate.\n*Sparrow - the chef at the army camp. Killed by Clardy after telling Jeff a secret about him.\n*Mike Dempsey- Older Irishman who befriends Jeff.\n*Ford Ivey- One of Jeff's best friends who was severely wounded during the [[Battle of Wilson's Creek]]. He eventually has his leg amputated.\n*Zed Tinney- God-fearing boy who owns a bible that is bound in black leather. Killed during the Battle of Wilson's Creek.\n*Jake Lonegan- A squad leader in Jeff's company.\n*Jim Veatch- Cardplayer in Jeff's company.\n*Neely North- A breezy recruit from [[Shawnee Mission]].\n*Walter Van Ostrand- A cowardly youngster in Jeff's company who purposely shot his gun off in order to be discharged.\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' said of the book: \"Stirring, original and always credible, this is distinctly superior.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/harold-keith-4/rifles-for-watie-2/ |journal=[[Kirkus Reviews]] |title=RIFLES FOR WATIE by Harold Keith |access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> In a retrospective essay about the Newbery Medal-winning books from 1956 to 1965, librarian Carolyn Horovitz wrote of ''Rifles for Watie'', ''[[Carry On, Mr. Bowditch]]'', ''[[The Witch of Blackbird Pond]]'' and ''[[The Bronze Bow]]'': \"All have value, all are told skilfully. If they lack the qualities of greatness, it is largely because their style has a commercial sameness.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Horovitz |first=Carolyn |chapter=Only the Best |page=[https://archive.org/details/newberycaldecott00king/page/160 160] |title=Newbery and Caldecott Medal Books: 1956-1965 |url=https://archive.org/details/newberycaldecott00king |url-access=registration |editor-last=Kingman |editor-first=Lee |publisher=[[The Horn Book Magazine|The Horn Book, Incorporated]] |location=[[Boston]] |year=1965 |lccn=65-26759}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* Winner, 1958 Newbery Medal\n* Notable Children's Books of 1957 (ALA)\n* 1964 James Carroll Shelf Award\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book | title=Rifles for Watide on Rifles for Watie | last= | first= | work=BookRags Study Guides | url=http://www.bookrags.com/studyguide-rifles-for-watie/ | date= | accessdate=2007-06-26 }}\n*{{cite book | title=Newbery and Caldecott Medal Books: 1956-1965 | url=https://archive.org/details/newberycaldecott00king | url-access=registration | last=Kingman | first=Lee (ed.) | publisher=Horn Book | location=Boston | year=1965 }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Newbery Medal|Newbery Medal recipient]]|before=''[[Miracles on Maple Hill]]''|after=''[[The Witch of Blackbird Pond]]''|years=[[1958 in literature|1958]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:1957 American novels]]\n[[Category:American Civil War novels]]\n[[Category:Children's historical novels]]\n[[Category:Newbery Medal-winning works]]\n[[Category:American children's novels]]\n[[Category:1957 children's books]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Kansas]]\n", "name_user": "2605:6000:1017:40ba:4cca:236:aece:ac8f", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCharacters)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rifles_for_Watie"}
{"title_page": "Esra Bilgi\u00e7", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Esra Bilgi\u00e7\n| image              = EsraBilgi\u00e7Actress.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1992|10|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = [[Turkey|Turkish]]\n| education          = [[Bilkent University]]<br>[[Hacettepe University]]\n| occupation         = Actress, model\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re]]|2017|2019|reason=div}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ntv.com.tr/galeri/yasam/gokhan-tore-esra-bilgici-ailesinden-boyle-istedi,04PekBPQcUaJlNIaxTl6IA/NbL8OlpzjU2eLKZraI0oAA|title=G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re, Esra Bilgi\u00e7'i ailesinden b\u00f6yle istedi|website=NTV}}</ref><ref name=\"turkishny.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.turkishny.com/sport-news/8-sport-news/255966-gokhan-tore-ile-esra-bilgic-evlendi|title=G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re ile Esra Bilgi\u00e7 Evlendi|access-date=2018-01-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102013325/http://www.turkishny.com/sport-news/8-sport-news/255966-gokhan-tore-ile-esra-bilgic-evlendi|archive-date=2018-01-02|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"div\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnturk.com/magazin/esra-bilgic-ile-gokhan-tore-bosandi|title=Esra Bilgi\u00e7 ile G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re bo\u015fand\u0131|publisher=CNN T\u00fcrk|date=17 June 2019|accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n| children           = \n| website            = \n}}\n<nowiki>{{}}</nowiki>\n\n'''[[Esra Bilgi\u00e7|Esra]] Bilgi\u00e7''' (born 14 October 1992)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haberturk.com/magazin/herkes-bunu-konusuyor/haber/1189311-esra-bilgic-kimdir|title=Esra Bilgi\u00e7 kimdir?|publisher=}}</ref> is a [[Turkey|Turkish]] actress and model. She portrayed [[Halime Hatun]] in the historical adventure television series ''[[Dirili\u015f: Ertu\u011frul]]'' from 2014 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aksam.com.tr/televizyon/dirilis-ertugrul-yeni-74-bolum-fragmani-son-bolum-trt-1de/haber-587343|title=Dirili\u015f Ertu\u011frul 74. yeni b\u00f6l\u00fcm fragman\u0131 TRT 1'de nefes kesti - Ak\u015fam|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mediaturkey.net/turkishdramas/dirilis-ertugrul-trt1-succes|title=Dirilis Ertugrul 's success is approved!|date=December 19, 2014|access-date=January 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530224836/http://www.mediaturkey.net/turkishdramas/dirilis-ertugrul-trt1-succes/|archive-date=May 30, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ahaber.com.tr/galeri/yasam/esra-bilgic-ve-gokhan-tore-mutluluga-evet-dedi|title=Esra Bilgi\u00e7 ve G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re mutlulu\u011fa 'evet' dedi|website=A Haber}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnturk.com/esra-bilgic|title=esra bilgi\u00e7 ile ilgili haberler|website=CNN T\u00fcrk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/cinema/2017/03/15/turkish-history-themed-series-dirilis-ertugrul-enjoyed-in-60-countries|title=Turkish history-themed series Dirili\u015f Ertu\u011frul enjoyed in 60 countries|publisher=|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trt.net.tr/espanol/cultura-y-arte/2016/12/07/la-trt-fue-premiada-en-varias-categorias-625259|title=La TRT fue premiada en varias categor\u00edas - TRT Espa\u00f1ol|website=www.trt.net.tr}}</ref> She is currently the leading actress in the crime drama series ''Ramo''.\n\n==Career==\n\nFrom 2014, She starred in the TV series ''[[Dirili\u015f: Ertu\u011frul]]'' telecast on [[TRT 1]]. Her co-actors were [[Engin Altan D\u00fczyatan]] and H\u00fclya Darcan. ''Dirili\u015f: Ertu\u011frul'' is about the heroic story of the father of [[Osman I]], [[Ertu\u011frul]], who turns a small tribe of Anatolya into a Sultanate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haberler.com/dirilis-ertugrul-yilin-en-populer-dizisi-oldu-9130237-haberi/|title=Dirili\u015f 'Ertu\u011frul' Y\u0131l\u0131n En Pop\u00fcler Dizisi Oldu!|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabah.com.tr/magazin/2017/10/22/esra-bilgic-ve-gokhan-tore-evlendi-iste-dugun-fotograflari|title=Esra Bilgi\u00e7 ve G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re d\u00fcn evlendi! - \u0130\u015fte d\u00fc\u011f\u00fcn foto\u011fraflar\u0131|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailysabah.com/nation/2014/12/11/turkeys-new-tv-series-about-the-founding-of-the-ottoman-empire-tops-the-ratings |title=Turkey's new TV series about the founding of the Ottoman empire tops the ratings|work= |first= |last= |date=December 12, 2014}}</ref> Esra Bilgi\u00e7 appeared as [[Halime Hatun]] in the series, but in 2018 she left ''Dirili\u015f: Ertu\u011frul'' because of the changes in the new season; her character, however, died in 1281, and not as early as it was shown in the TV series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/magazin/2016/11/02/gokhan-tore-ile-esra-bilgic-gizlice-nisanlandi|title=G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re ile Esra Bilgi\u00e7 gizlice ni\u015fanland\u0131|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haberakar.com/dirilis-ertugrulun-halimesi-esra-bilgic-gokhan-tore-ile-nisanlandi-haberi-15834|title=Dirili\u015f Ertu\u011frul'un Halime'si Esra Bilgi\u00e7 G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re ile ni\u015fanland\u0131|date=2 November 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haberler.com/gokhan-tore-oyuncu-sevgilisi-esra-bilgic-le-8116925-haberi/|title=G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re, Oyuncu Sevgilisi Esra Bilgi\u00e7'le Evleniyor|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aksam.com.tr/magazin/esra-bilgic-ile-gokhan-tore-evleniyor/haber-485757|title=Esra Bilgi\u00e7 ile G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re evleniyor - Ak\u015fam|publisher=}}</ref>\nEsra also appeared in ''Bir Umut Yeter''. In 2019, Bilgi\u00e7 was asked to play a leading role in the film ''Adani\u015f Kutsal Kavga''. The film will be released in March, 2020. She is currently the female lead in the Turkish crime-drama TV series ''Ramo'', which co-stars [[Murat_Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m_(actor)|Murat Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m]].{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Personal life==\nEsra Bilgi\u00e7 began dating a professional Turkish footballer, [[G\u00f6khan T\u00f6re]], in 2014. The couple got married on 21 October 2017 and divorced on 17 June 2019. <ref name=\"div\"/> She studied the subject of \"International Relations\" at Bilkent International University, Istanbul,<ref name=\"turkishny.com\"/> and is currently studying law at \u0130stanbul \u015eehir University.<ref>{{cite web|title=Esra Bilgi\u00e7 - Twitter|publisher=|url=https://twitter.com/esbilgic/status/1209535240420700161}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:LightSteelBlue\"|TV Series\n|-\n!style=\"background:#CCCCCC\"| Year\n!style=\"background:#CCCCCC\"| Title\n!style=\"background:#CCCCCC\"| Role\n!style=\"background:#CCCCCC\"| Note \n|-\n|2014\u20132018\n|''[[Dirili\u015f: Ertu\u011frul]]''\n|[[Halime Hatun]]\n|Main role\n|-\n|2018\n|''Bir Umut Yeter''\n|Derya Akar\n|Main role\n|-\n|2020\n|''Ramo''\n|Sibel Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m\n|Main role\n|} \n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:LightSteelBlue\"|Films\n|-\n!style=\"background:#CCCCCC\"| Year\n!style=\"background:#CCCCCC\"| Title\n!style=\"background:#CCCCCC\"| Role\n!style=\"background:#CCCCCC\"| Note \n|-\n|2020\n|''Adani\u015f Kutsal Kavga''\n| Cemre\n|Main role\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{refimprove section|date=November 2019}}\nBilgi\u00e7 has won several awards. Some of them are: \n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! colspan=5 style=\"background:LightSteelBlue\"| Awards\n|-\n!style=\"background:#CCCCCC\"| Year\n!style=\"background:#CCC